export default "<!-- target: zh | interface: en | version: 1 -->\n<!-- Mandarin Chinese. Extra chapters: tones & pinyin (make-or-break), measure words/classifiers, aspect particles (了/过/着), the 把 construction — structurally unavoidable. -->\n\n# Pronunciation & Pinyin — the Four Tones <!-- slug: pronunciation-pinyin-tones -->\n\nMandarin has no alphabet. **Pinyin** is the romanization system used to write sounds — it is a learning tool, not the language. Every syllable in Mandarin has a **tone**, and the tone is as much a part of the word as the consonants and vowels. Getting tones wrong doesn't produce an accent — it produces a different word.\n\n## The Five Tones <!-- slug: tones -->\n\n| Tone | Mark | Description | Example |\n|------|------|-------------|---------|\n| 1st — high level | ā | held high and flat, like singing a sustained note | 妈 (mā) — mother |\n| 2nd — rising | á | rises sharply, like asking \"huh?\" | 麻 (má) — hemp/numb |\n| 3rd — dipping | ǎ | starts mid, dips low, then rises | 马 (mǎ) — horse |\n| 4th — falling | à | drops hard and fast from high to low | 骂 (mà) — scold |\n| Neutral — unstressed | a | short, light, no tone mark | 吗 (ma) — question particle |\n\n**mā má mǎ mà ma** — five distinct words from one syllable. This is the make-or-break reality of Mandarin. The 3rd tone is hardest: it rarely gets the full dip-and-rise except in isolation; before another syllable it often just drops low.\n\n## Tone Sandhi — when tones change in context <!-- slug: tone-sandhi -->\n\nTwo rules you must internalize:\n\n**不 (bù, \"not\")** is 4th tone by default. But before another 4th-tone syllable it becomes 2nd: *bù + 去 (qù)* → **bú qù** (not going). Before any other tone it stays 4th.\n\n**一 (yī, \"one/a\")** is 1st tone in isolation. Before 4th tone → 2nd: *yī + 个 (gè)* → **yí gè**. Before 1st/2nd/3rd tone → 4th: *yī + 天 (tiān)* → **yì tiān** (one day). In ordinal position or alone, stays 1st.\n\n**Two consecutive 3rd tones**: the first becomes 2nd tone: *你好 (nǐ hǎo)* — spoken as **ní hǎo** (the first syllable rises). This is why \"hello\" doesn't sound like two dipping tones.\n\n## Initials & Finals <!-- slug: initials-finals -->\n\nPinyin syllables = **initial** (consonant onset) + **final** (vowel nucleus + ending). Tricky ones for English speakers:\n\n**Initials:**\n- **x** = like English \"sh\" but with your tongue flat against the bottom teeth, not curled: *xīn* (heart)\n- **q** = \"ch\" with tongue flat: *qǐng* (please)\n- **zh/ch/sh/r** = retroflex — tongue curls back slightly: *zhōngguó* (China). Contrast with flat **z/c/s**: *zì* (character) vs *zhī* (to know)\n- **j** = like English \"j\" but never voiced heavily: *jiā* (home)\n- **r** is not rolled — it's more like an English \"r\" merged with \"zh\": *rén* (person)\n\n**Finals:**\n- **e** alone = the \"uh\" sound, not \"eh\": *hē* (drink)\n- **ui** = actually \"uei\": *duì* (correct)\n- **-n vs -ng**: *mān* (slow) vs *máng* (busy) — the nasal ending matters\n- **ü** = German ü, French u — round your lips for \"ee\": *lǘ* (donkey). After **j/q/x/y** the dots are dropped: *jū* = *jü*\n\n## The English-speaker trap <!-- slug: tones-trap -->\n\nEnglish uses pitch for **emotion and sentence grammar** (rising for questions, etc.). In Mandarin, pitch belongs to the **word**. Your brain will fight you and try to put 3rd/4th tones on words that feel like questions or uncertain statements. Consciously override this — the tone stays on the word no matter how you feel about the sentence.\n\n✗ Common error: saying *nǐ hǎo* with a rising intonation on *hǎo* to sound \"polite\" — this turns it into 2nd+2nd or something undefined.\n✓ Keep the tones steady; use filler words and particles for emotional tone.\n\n---\n\n# Chinese Characters — Hanzi <!-- slug: hanzi-characters -->\n\nCharacters are the written form of the language. Each character = one syllable = (usually) one morpheme. You don't need thousands to start, but you need some foundation.\n\n## How characters are built <!-- slug: radicals-structure -->\n\nMost characters are **compound**: they combine a **semantic radical** (hint at meaning) with a **phonetic component** (hint at pronunciation). Example:\n\n- 语 (*yǔ* — language): radical 讠(speech/language) + 吾 (*wú*, phonetically similar) → something related to speech\n- 请 (*qǐng* — please/invite): 讠(speech) + 青 (*qīng*, phonetically hints at \"qing\") → polite speech\n\n**Radicals** are the left/top component that carries semantic flavor. Common ones:\n- 讠= speech/language: 说, 话, 语, 请\n- 氵= water: 海, 河, 洗, 泳\n- 木 = wood/tree: 树, 桌, 椅, 林\n- 人/亻= person: 他, 们, 做, 你\n- 口 = mouth/speech: 吃, 喝, 叫, 问\n\nLearning radicals = shortcut for both memory and guessing. If you see 氵on a character you've never met, it probably relates to water or liquid.\n\n## Strokes <!-- slug: strokes -->\n\nCharacters are built from **strokes**, written in a fixed order (generally top→bottom, left→right). Stroke order affects legibility and handwriting fluency. The main stroke types: horizontal (一), vertical (丨), left-falling (丿), right-falling (㇏), dot (丶), hook (乚).\n\n## Simplified vs Traditional <!-- slug: simplified-traditional -->\n\nMainland China uses **simplified characters** (简体字, jiǎntǐzì) — reformed in the 1950s–60s to reduce stroke counts. Taiwan, Hong Kong, and overseas communities often use **traditional characters** (繁體字, fántǐzì). This guide uses simplified.\n\nExamples: 爱 (simplified) vs 愛 (traditional) — \"love\"; 书 vs 書 — \"book\".\n\n## Characters map one-to-one with syllables <!-- slug: syllable-map -->\n\nA crucial structural fact: every character is exactly one syllable. There are no multi-syllable characters. Most modern Chinese *words* are **two characters/syllables**:\n- 电话 (*diànhuà*) — telephone (electric + speech)\n- 朋友 (*péngyǒu*) — friend (companion + friend)\n- 学习 (*xuéxí*) — study (learn + practice)\n\nThis means reading speed ≈ recognizing character-pairs, not individual symbols.\n\n---\n\n# Basic Word Order <!-- slug: word-order -->\n\nMandarin is fundamentally **SVO** (Subject–Verb–Object) like English, but with one deeper organizing principle: **topic-comment structure**.\n\n## SVO and topic-comment <!-- slug: topic-comment -->\n\nIn a topic-comment sentence, whatever is being *talked about* (the topic) comes first — even if grammatically it's the object:\n\n*这本书我看过了。(Zhè běn shū wǒ kàn guò le.)* — \"This book, I've (already) read it.\"\n— the book is the topic, the rest is the comment. Chinese does this constantly and naturally.\n\n## Time and place before the verb <!-- slug: time-place-order -->\n\n**Temporal and locative expressions come BEFORE the verb** — the opposite of English default:\n\n| Chinese | Pinyin | English |\n|---------|--------|---------|\n| 我**明天**去 | wǒ **míngtiān** qù | I'm going tomorrow |\n| 他**在北京**工作 | tā **zài Běijīng** gōngzuò | He works in Beijing |\n| 我**每天早上**喝咖啡 | wǒ **měitiān zǎoshang** hē kāfēi | I drink coffee every morning |\n\nOrder within the pre-verb zone: **Subject → Time → Place → Verb → Object**. \"Yesterday in Shanghai I ate dumplings\" → *我昨天在上海吃了饺子。*\n\n✗ Don't calque English: ~~*我吃了饺子在上海昨天*~~ — Chinese doesn't shuffle post-verb the way English does.\n\n---\n\n# Measure Words / Classifiers <!-- slug: measure-words -->\n\n*(Language-specific chapter: mandatory between any number or demonstrative and a noun.)*\n\nIn English you say \"three books.\" In Chinese you cannot say *三书* — you must insert a **measure word** (量词, liàngcí, also called classifier): **三本书** (*sān běn shū*, three [volume] books).\n\nThe same applies with 这 (zhè — this) and 那 (nà — that): 这**本**书 (this book), 那**个**人 (that person).\n\n## 个 (gè) — the default <!-- slug: measure-word-ge -->\n\n**个** is the most common classifier and works as a safe fallback for people and many general nouns when you can't remember the specific one. It's slightly informal but widely understood.\n\n| Measure Word | Used for | Examples |\n|---|---|---|\n| 个 (gè) | people, general objects (fallback) | 一个人 (one person), 两个苹果 (two apples) |\n| 本 (běn) | bound books, notebooks | 三本书 (three books) |\n| 张 (zhāng) | flat things: paper, tables, tickets, faces | 一张票 (one ticket), 两张桌子 (two tables) |\n| 条 (tiáo) | long, flexible things: rivers, roads, fish, pants | 一条鱼 (one fish), 两条腿 (two legs) |\n| 只 (zhī) | small animals, one of a pair | 一只猫 (one cat), 一只手 (one hand) |\n| 件 (jiàn) | items: clothes, affairs, luggage | 一件衬衫 (one shirt) |\n| 杯 (bēi) | cups/glasses of liquid | 一杯水 (one glass of water) |\n| 瓶 (píng) | bottles | 一瓶啤酒 (one bottle of beer) |\n| 位 (wèi) | people (polite/respectful) | 一位老师 (one teacher — respectful) |\n| 把 (bǎ) | things with handles: chairs, knives, umbrellas | 一把椅子 (one chair) |\n\n**Mnemonic**: think of measure words as telling you the *shape or category* of the object. 张 = flat surface. 条 = long and bendy. 只 = small and singular.\n\n✗ *三书* — missing classifier\n✓ *三本书* (three books)\n\nNumbers 两 (liǎng) vs 二 (èr): use **两** before measure words (*两个人* — two people), **二** for counting in sequences (二, 三, 四...) and math.\n\n---\n\n# Pronouns & Possession with 的 <!-- slug: pronouns-possession -->\n\n## Personal Pronouns <!-- slug: personal-pronouns -->\n\n| | Singular | Plural |\n|---|---|---|\n| 1st | 我 wǒ (I/me) | 我们 wǒmen (we/us) |\n| 2nd | 你 nǐ (you) / 您 nín (polite you) | 你们 nǐmen (you all) |\n| 3rd | 他 tā (he/him) / 她 tā (she/her) / 它 tā (it) | 他们 tāmen / 她们 tāmen |\n\n**他/她/它** sound identical in speech — all *tā*. Context resolves gender; spoken Mandarin is effectively genderless.\n\n**您 (nín)** is the formal/respectful \"you\" — use with elders, strangers in service contexts, teachers.\n\n## 的 (de) — the possession particle <!-- slug: de-possession -->\n\n**的** after a pronoun (or noun) marks possession, like an apostrophe-s:\n\n- 我的书 (*wǒ de shū*) — my book\n- 她的朋友 (*tā de péngyǒu*) — her friend\n- 中国的文化 (*Zhōngguó de wénhuà*) — China's culture / Chinese culture\n\nBetween **close relationships and short phrases**, 的 is often dropped colloquially:\n- 我妈 (my mom) — not 我的妈妈 in casual speech\n- 我们学校 (our school)\n\n**的 also links adjectives to nouns** — see the Adjectives chapter.\n\n---\n\n# Verbs Never Conjugate <!-- slug: verbs-no-conjugation -->\n\nThis is genuinely liberating: **Mandarin verbs do not change form — ever.**\n\n- No person agreement: *我去 / 你去 / 他去 / 我们去* — \"I go / you go / he goes / we go\" — same 去 every time\n- No tense conjugation: *我去* can mean \"I go,\" \"I went,\" or \"I will go\" depending on context\n- No infinitive vs finite distinction\n\nThe same verb form appears in every slot. This means **tense and aspect are handled by other means** — time words and aspect particles (see next chapter).\n\n**Common verbs (no forms to memorize):**\n\n| Verb | Pinyin | Meaning |\n|---|---|---|\n| 是 | shì | to be (for identity/classification) |\n| 有 | yǒu | to have / there is |\n| 去 | qù | to go |\n| 来 | lái | to come |\n| 吃 | chī | to eat |\n| 喝 | hē | to drink |\n| 说 | shuō | to speak/say |\n| 做 | zuò | to do/make |\n| 看 | kàn | to watch/read/look |\n| 听 | tīng | to listen |\n| 买 | mǎi | to buy |\n| 知道 | zhīdào | to know (a fact) |\n| 认识 | rènshi | to know (a person) |\n\n---\n\n# Aspect, Not Tense — 了, 过, 在/正在, 着 <!-- slug: aspect-particles -->\n\n*(Language-specific chapter: Mandarin marks HOW an action relates to completion or duration, not WHEN it happened.)*\n\nChinese doesn't conjugate for tense the way European languages do. Instead, **aspect particles** tell you about the *shape* of the action — completed, ever-experienced, ongoing, or continuing.\n\n## 了 (le) — completion & change of state <!-- slug: aspect-le -->\n\n**了** has two distinct jobs. Getting them mixed up is one of the most common intermediate-level errors.\n\n**Job 1 — verbal 了**: goes directly after the verb, signals the **action is completed**:\n- 我吃了饭。(*Wǒ chī le fàn.*) — I ate / I have eaten (the meal is done)\n- 他买了一本书。(*Tā mǎi le yī běn shū.*) — He bought a book.\n\n**Job 2 — modal/sentence-final 了**: goes at the END of the sentence, signals a **new situation or change of state**:\n- 下雨了。(*Xià yǔ le.*) — It's started raining. (change: rain began)\n- 我饿了。(*Wǒ è le.*) — I'm hungry now. (I wasn't before — change)\n- 我不去了。(*Wǒ bù qù le.*) — I'm not going anymore. (changed my mind)\n\nBoth 了s can appear together: 我吃了饭了 — I've already eaten (the first marks completion, the second marks the current state of having eaten).\n\n✗ Don't equate 了 with \"past tense\" — it can appear in future contexts too: *你吃了再走。* (Eat first, then leave.)\n\n## 过 (guo) — experienced ever <!-- slug: aspect-guo -->\n\nMarks that something was **ever experienced** at some point in one's life — not about when, just whether:\n- 你去过中国吗？(*Nǐ qù guo Zhōngguó ma?*) — Have you ever been to China?\n- 我没去过。(*Wǒ méi qù guo.*) — I've never been.\n- 我吃过北京烤鸭。(*Wǒ chī guo Běijīng kǎoyā.*) — I've (had the experience of) eaten Peking Duck.\n\n## 在/正在 and 着 (zhe) — ongoing and durative <!-- slug: aspect-ongoing -->\n\n**在/正在** before the verb = action is **in progress right now** (like English \"-ing\"):\n- 我在看书。(*Wǒ zài kàn shū.*) — I'm reading.\n- 她正在睡觉。(*Tā zhèngzài shuìjiào.*) — She's sleeping (right now, emphatic).\n\n**着 (zhe)** after the verb = a **continuing state** (the result of an action persists):\n- 门开着。(*Mén kāi zhe.*) — The door is open. (opened, and remains open)\n- 他站着说话。(*Tā zhàn zhe shuōhuà.*) — He's talking while standing. (maintains standing posture)\n- 墙上挂着一幅画。(*Qiáng shàng guà zhe yī fú huà.*) — A picture is hanging on the wall.\n\n---\n\n# Negation — 不 vs 没(有) <!-- slug: negation -->\n\nTwo negators, and the split is crucial:\n\n## 不 (bù) — general, habitual, future, will <!-- slug: negation-bu -->\n\n**不** negates **general facts, habitual actions, present states, future intentions, and adjectives/modal verbs**:\n- 我不喝酒。(*Wǒ bù hē jiǔ.*) — I don't drink alcohol. (general/habitual)\n- 我不去。(*Wǒ bù qù.*) — I'm not going. (future intention)\n- 他不高。(*Tā bù gāo.*) — He's not tall. (adjective/state)\n- 我不想吃。(*Wǒ bù xiǎng chī.*) — I don't want to eat.\n\n**不** also negates 是 (to be): *我不是学生。* (I'm not a student.)\n\n## 没(有) (méi/méiyǒu) — past actions, have/haven't <!-- slug: negation-mei -->\n\n**没(有)** negates **completed actions** (the negative counterpart of verbal 了) and **possession** (negates 有):\n- 我没吃饭。(*Wǒ méi chī fàn.*) — I didn't eat. / I haven't eaten.\n- 他没来。(*Tā méi lái.*) — He didn't come.\n- 我没有车。(*Wǒ méi yǒu chē.*) — I don't have a car.\n\n**Critical contrast:**\n- *我不吃肉。* — I don't eat meat (general — vegetarian, lifestyle)\n- *我没吃肉。* — I didn't eat meat (yesterday, on that occasion)\n\n✗ *我不吃了饭* — wrong. 了 marks completion; negate completion with 没, not 不.\n✓ *我没吃饭。*\n\n---\n\n# Questions <!-- slug: questions -->\n\n## 吗 (ma) — yes/no questions <!-- slug: question-ma -->\n\nAdd 吗 to the end of any statement to make it a yes/no question. Word order **does not change** — no inversion:\n- 你是学生。→ 你是学生**吗**？(*Nǐ shì xuésheng ma?*) — Are you a student?\n- 他来了**吗**？— Has he come?\n\nAnswer with the verb, not \"yes/no\":\n- 是 (*shì*) / 不是 (*bú shì*) — yes (it is) / no (it's not)\n- 来了 / 没来 — yes (came) / no (didn't come)\n\n## 呢 (ne) — \"what about…?\" <!-- slug: question-ne -->\n\nLightweight particle for follow-up questions, meaning \"and you? / what about X?\":\n- *我很好，你**呢**？* — I'm fine, and you?\n- *他去了，她**呢**？* — He went, what about her?\n\n## A-not-A questions <!-- slug: question-a-not-a -->\n\nRepeat the verb in positive-negative form — a question without a question word or particle:\n- 你去**不去**？(*Nǐ qù bu qù?*) — Are you going (or not)?\n- 他是**不是**学生？(*Tā shì bu shì xuésheng?*) — Is he a student?\n- 你喜欢**不喜欢**？(*Nǐ xǐhuan bu xǐhuan?*) — Do you like it?\n\nWith 有: *你有**没有**时间？* — Do you have time?\n\n## Question words stay in place <!-- slug: question-words-in-place -->\n\n**This is a major structural difference from English.** In Mandarin, question words sit in the position that answers them — the sentence order doesn't change:\n\n| Question | Pinyin | Literal | English |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 你叫**什么**名字？ | Nǐ jiào **shénme** míngzi? | You called what name? | What's your name? |\n| **谁**来了？ | **Shéi** lái le? | Who came? | Who came? |\n| 你去**哪儿**？ | Nǐ qù **nǎr**? | You go where? | Where are you going? |\n| 你**为什么**不吃？ | Nǐ **wèishénme** bù chī? | You why not eat? | Why aren't you eating? |\n| 这个**多少钱**？ | Zhège **duōshao qián**? | This how much money? | How much is this? |\n| **什么时候**去？ | **Shénme shíhou** qù? | What time go? | When are we going? |\n\n✓ 好吗？(*hǎo ma?*) — OK? / all right?\n✓ 对吧？(*duì ba?*) — right? / isn't it? (seeking confirmation, like a tag question)\n✓ 是吗？(*shì ma?*) — really? (surprised)\n\n---\n\n# Adjectives as Predicates <!-- slug: adjectives-predicates -->\n\n## No 是 with adjectives — a classic trap <!-- slug: adjectives-no-shi -->\n\nIn English: \"He is tall.\" In Chinese you do NOT say *他是高* — **是** is not used with adjectives as predicates. The adjective itself serves as the predicate verb:\n\n- 他很高。(*Tā hěn gāo.*) — He is tall.\n- 这本书很好。(*Zhè běn shū hěn hǎo.*) — This book is good.\n\nThe **很** (*hěn*, \"very\") is almost always present even when you don't mean \"very\" — without it, the sentence sounds like a **comparison** or is pragmatically incomplete. Think of 很 as a grammatical buffer rather than a true intensifier here.\n\n✗ 他高。— grammatically implies \"he is taller (than something)\" or sounds like a list entry\n✓ 他很高。— natural statement \"he's tall\"\n\nFor genuine \"very\": double it or use 非常 (*fēicháng*, extremely):\n- 她非常漂亮。(*Tā fēicháng piàoliang.*) — She's extremely beautiful.\n\n## 是...的 construction <!-- slug: shi-de-construction -->\n\nThis structure focuses on the **circumstances of a completed action** — when, where, how, by whom:\n- 他是**昨天来**的。(*Tā shì zuótiān lái de.*) — He came **yesterday**. (emphasis: it was yesterday)\n- 我是**在北京**学的中文。(*Wǒ shì zài Běijīng xué de Zhōngwén.*) — I learned Chinese **in Beijing**.\n- 这个是**谁做**的？(*Zhège shì shéi zuò de?*) — Who made this?\n\nIt's about a past fact already known — you're zooming in on the *details* of how it happened.\n\n---\n\n# Comparisons with 比 <!-- slug: comparisons-bi -->\n\nThe standard comparison structure uses **比** (bǐ — compared to):\n\n**A 比 B + adjective** = A is [adj]-er than B\n\n- 他比我高。(*Tā bǐ wǒ gāo.*) — He's taller than me.\n- 北京比上海冷。(*Běijīng bǐ Shànghǎi lěng.*) — Beijing is colder than Shanghai.\n- 今天比昨天热多了。(*Jīntiān bǐ zuótiān rè duō le.*) — Today is much hotter than yesterday. (多了 = by a lot)\n\n✗ Don't add 更 (*gèng*, \"even more\") in a basic 比 sentence — the adjective alone carries the comparative meaning.\n✗ *他比我更高* — technically possible but overloaded; stick with *他比我高*.\n\n**Equality — 跟...一样 (gēn...yīyàng):**\n- 他跟我一样高。(*Tā gēn wǒ yīyàng gāo.*) — He's as tall as me.\n\n**Superlative — 最 (zuì):**\n- 她是班里最高的。(*Tā shì bān lǐ zuì gāo de.*) — She's the tallest in the class.\n\n---\n\n# Coverbs / Prepositions <!-- slug: coverbs-prepositions -->\n\nMandarin \"prepositions\" are better called **coverbs** — they are historically verbs that now function prepositionally. They come before the main verb and introduce the context of the action.\n\n| Coverb | Pinyin | Function | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 在 | zài | location of action | 我在家工作。— I work at home. |\n| 给 | gěi | for / give to (beneficiary) | 我给你买了礼物。— I bought you a gift. |\n| 跟 | gēn | with (accompanying) | 我跟他一起去。— I'm going with him. |\n| 从 | cóng | from (starting point) | 他从北京来。— He comes from Beijing. |\n| 到 | dào | to / arrive at | 我到学校了。— I've arrived at school. |\n| 对 | duì | toward / regarding | 她对我很好。— She's very good to me. |\n| 离 | lí | distance from | 图书馆离这儿不远。— The library isn't far from here. |\n| 用 | yòng | using / by means of | 你用筷子吃吗？— Do you eat with chopsticks? |\n| 向/往 | xiàng/wǎng | toward (direction) | 向右走。— Walk to the right. |\n| 为 | wèi | for the sake of | 我为你高兴。— I'm happy for you. |\n\n---\n\n# Modal / Auxiliary Verbs <!-- slug: modal-verbs -->\n\nThese go before the main verb and never change form.\n\n## Ability and possibility <!-- slug: modal-ability -->\n\n| Word | Pinyin | Meaning | Note |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 会 | huì | can (learned skill) / will likely | 我会游泳。— I can swim. |\n| 能 | néng | can (circumstantially able) | 我今天不能来。— I can't come today. |\n| 可以 | kěyǐ | may / permitted to | 我可以进来吗？— May I come in? |\n\n**会 vs 能**: 会 = acquired skill (\"I know how to\"), 能 = conditions allow (\"I'm able to right now\"). A broken leg: *我不能走* (I can't walk — capacity gone), not *我不会走* (which would mean I never learned to walk).\n\n## Desire and obligation <!-- slug: modal-desire-obligation -->\n\n| Word | Pinyin | Meaning | Example |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| 想 | xiǎng | want to / think about | 我想喝水。— I want some water. |\n| 要 | yào | want / need / will (future) | 我要一杯咖啡。— I'd like a coffee. |\n| 应该 | yīnggāi | should / ought to | 你应该多休息。— You should rest more. |\n| 得 | děi | must (necessity) | 我得走了。— I have to go now. |\n| 必须 | bìxū | must (strong obligation) | 你必须来。— You must come. |\n\n**要 is multipurpose** — it can mean \"want,\" \"need,\" \"going to,\" or signal future: *要下雨了* — it's going to rain.\n\n---\n\n# The 把 Construction <!-- slug: ba-construction -->\n\n*(Language-specific chapter: notoriously tricky — the \"disposal\" construction.)*\n\n**把** (bǎ) moves the object to a **pre-verbal position** to emphasize what happens *to* it. Think of it as saying: \"take X and do something with it.\"\n\n**Structure: Subject + 把 + Object + Verb + Result/Complement**\n\n- 我把书放在桌子上。(*Wǒ bǎ shū fàng zài zhuōzi shàng.*) — I put the book on the table.\n- 她把作业做完了。(*Tā bǎ zuòyè zuò wán le.*) — She finished the homework. (did it to completion)\n- 他把我的名字写错了。(*Tā bǎ wǒ de míngzi xiě cuò le.*) — He wrote my name wrong.\n\n## When to use 把 <!-- slug: ba-when -->\n\nUse it when:\n1. You're emphasizing what is **done to** a specific, definite object\n2. The verb has a **result or direction** attached (a complement)\n3. The object is somehow **affected, moved, or disposed of**\n\n✗ *我把书看。* — wrong. The verb needs a result complement. Can't just say \"I 把-ed the book looked.\"\n✓ *我把书看完了。* — I finished reading the book.\n\n✗ *我把一本书买了。* — doesn't work well. 把 objects must be **definite** (known, specific). Use: *我买了一本书。*\n✓ *我把那本书买了。* — I bought that book (the specific one).\n\n**Negation and modals go BEFORE 把:**\n- 我没把作业做完。— I didn't finish the homework.\n- 你应该把手机关掉。— You should turn off your phone.\n\n---\n\n# Complex Sentences <!-- slug: complex-sentences -->\n\n## Because...therefore: 因为...所以 <!-- slug: complex-yinwei-suoyi -->\n\nChinese often states both halves of a causal relationship explicitly — using both 因为 AND 所以 in a single sentence (which feels redundant to English speakers, but is natural in Chinese):\n\n- 因为下雨，所以我没去。(*Yīnwèi xià yǔ, suǒyǐ wǒ méi qù.*) — Because it rained, (so) I didn't go.\n- 因为他工作很忙，所以没时间。— Because he's busy with work, (so) he has no time.\n\nOne can be dropped in informal speech, but using both is always correct.\n\n## Although...but: 虽然...但是 <!-- slug: complex-suiran-danshi -->\n\nSame paired structure — use both halves:\n- 虽然贵，但是很好。(*Suīrán guì, dànshì hěn hǎo.*) — Although it's expensive, it's very good.\n- 虽然他很累，但是还在工作。— Although he's tired, he's still working.\n\n✗ Don't use 但是 without 虽然 if you're using the paired structure — they go together.\nNote: English says \"although...but\" is redundant; Chinese requires it.\n\n## 一边...一边 — doing two things simultaneously <!-- slug: complex-yibian -->\n\n- 他一边听音乐，一边写作业。(*Tā yībiān tīng yīnyuè, yībiān xiě zuòyè.*) — He listens to music while doing homework.\n- 我们一边喝茶，一边聊天。— We chat while drinking tea.\n\n---\n\n# Conditionals — 如果/要是...就 <!-- slug: conditionals -->\n\nThe standard conditional pattern:\n\n**如果/要是 + condition clause + 就 + result clause**\n\n- 如果明天下雨，我就不去了。(*Rúguǒ míngtiān xià yǔ, wǒ jiù bù qù le.*) — If it rains tomorrow, I won't go.\n- 要是你有时间，就来找我。(*Yàoshi nǐ yǒu shíjiān, jiù lái zhǎo wǒ.*) — If you have time, come find me.\n- 如果你不学，就不会说中文。— If you don't study, you won't be able to speak Chinese.\n\n**就** (jiù) in the result clause is like a logical \"then\" — it's often optional but makes the sentence flow naturally. Without a conditional opener, 就 alone signals immediacy or inevitability:\n- 我现在就去。— I'll go right now.\n\n**Unreal conditions** use the same structure — context makes it clear:\n- 如果我有很多钱，就买一栋大房子。— If I had a lot of money, I'd buy a big house.\n\n---\n\n# Describing a Movie <!-- slug: describing-a-movie -->\n\nPlot is typically narrated in **present tense** (no aspect particles, just bare verbs — or 在 for ongoing scenes).\n\n**Basic description structure:**\n\n1. **Genre and basics:**\n   - 这是一部**爱情片/动作片/恐怖片/科幻片/纪录片**。(*Zhè shì yī bù àiqíngpiān / dòngzuòpiān / kǒngbùpiān / kēhuànpiān / jìlùpiān.*) — This is a romance/action/horror/sci-fi/documentary.\n   - 这部电影是**XX导演**拍的。(*Zhè bù diànyǐng shì XX dǎoyǎn pāi de.*) — This film was directed by XX.\n   - 故事发生在... (*Gùshi fāshēng zài...*) — The story takes place in...\n\n2. **Plot:**\n   - 这部电影讲的是... (*Zhè bù diànyǐng jiǎng de shì...*) — This film is about...\n   - 主人公是一个... (*Zhǔréngōng shì yī gè...*) — The main character is a...\n   - 最后... (*Zuìhòu...*) — In the end...\n\n3. **Opinion:**\n   - 我觉得这部电影很好看。(*Wǒ juéde zhè bù diànyǐng hěn hǎokàn.*) — I think this film is great.\n   - 演员演得很好。(*Yǎnyuán yǎn de hěn hǎo.*) — The acting is very good. (结果补语 structure: V + 得 + assessment)\n   - 剧情很精彩/很无聊。(*Jùqíng hěn jīngcǎi / hěn wúliáo.*) — The plot is fantastic / boring.\n   - 结局很出乎意料。(*Jiéjú hěn chū hū yìliào.*) — The ending is very unexpected.\n   - 我强烈推荐！(*Wǒ qiángliè tuījiàn!*) — I strongly recommend it!\n   - 值得一看。(*Zhídé yī kàn.*) — Worth watching.\n\n**Vocabulary:**\n- 电影 (*diànyǐng*) — film/movie; 电视剧 (*diànshìjù*) — TV series\n- 导演 (*dǎoyǎn*) — director; 演员 (*yǎnyuán*) — actor/actress\n- 主角/主人公 (*zhǔjué/zhǔréngōng*) — main character; 反派 (*fǎnpài*) — villain\n- 情节/剧情 (*qíngjié/jùqíng*) — plot; 结局 (*jiéjú*) — ending\n- 特效 (*tèxiào*) — special effects; 配乐 (*pèiyuè*) — soundtrack\n- 感人 (*gǎnrén*) — moving/touching; 刺激 (*cìjī*) — thrilling; 搞笑 (*gǎoxiào*) — funny\n";
